{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AmhVkZizi2XSNnQreLfzwh","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! Now I have a comprehensive understanding. Let me create a summary document:\n\nNow I have a complete picture of the chicago-mcp-contract.md and the test patterns. Let me compile the comprehensive report:\n\n## Summary Report: Chicago-MCP Contract and Test Patterns\n\n### 1. Chicago-MCP Contract Contents\n\nThe **chicago-mcp-contract.md** defines Rust contracts for computer-use MCP while isolating high-privilege behavior from generic MCP runtime. Here are the key sections:\n\n**Core Contracts (Rust Sketch):**\n- `McpServerRef`: Struct containing server name and computer-use request flags\n- `CapabilityLevel`: Enum with `Standard` and `PrivilegedComputerUse` variants\n- `McpCapabilityPolicy` trait: Validates server names and determines capability levels\n- `ComputerUseLifecycle` trait: Three async lifecycle hooks:\n  - `before_tool_call()` - Called before executing a tool\n  - `after_turn_cleanup()` - Called at normal turn end\n  - `on_interrupt_cleanup()` - Called on interrupt/abort\n\n**Error Taxonomy:**\n1. `ReservedServerName` - Hard-rejected reserved names\n2. `FeatureGateDisabled` - Gate not enabled  \n3. `PrivilegedCapabilityDenied` - Policy doesn't allow privileged mode\n4. `TransportError` - MCP protocol transport issue\n5. `InvalidToolPayload` - Malformed tool request/response\n6. `CleanupFailed` - Non-fatal in interrupt path\n\n**Policy Rules:**\n1. Reserved names are hard-rejected before persistence\n2. Privileged computer-use requires both gate + policy pass\n3. Cleanup must run in both normal and interrupt paths\n4. Cleanup failures don't crash main turn path\n\n**Acceptance Matrix:**\n- **Contract tests**: Reserved names rejected, privileged denied without gate, cleanup API called for both exits\n- **Integration tests**: Registration + dispatch happy path, interrupt triggers cleanup once, cleanup exception doesn't poison turns\n- **CLI behavior tests**: `--computer-use-mcp` routes correctly, errors are deterministic, disabled gate gives reason\n\n---\n\n### 2. Test File Patterns Used\n\n**File naming and location:**\n- Acceptance tests: `{feature_name}_acceptance_tests.rs` (e.g., `bridge_mode_acceptance_tests.rs`)\n- Test modules: Inline in lib.rs via `#[cfg(test)] mod {test_name};`\n- Unit tests: `{feature_name}_tests.rs` or inline `mod tests { ... }` with `#[test]` or `#[tokio::test]`\n\n**Structure pattern from bridge_mode_acceptance_tests.rs:**\n```rust\n/// Feature acceptance tests (US-XXX)\n/// \n/// Covers all scenarios from {contract}.md §8 Acceptance Criteria:\n///   §8.1 Contract tests  – transport and policy layer invariants\n///   §8.2 Integration tests – multi-step lifecycle flows\n///\n/// CLI behaviour tests live in crates/cli/src/cmd/{feature}.rs.\nuse crate::{/* imports */};\nuse std::/* std imports */;\nuse tokio::sync::Mutex;\n\n// ── shared test doubles ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n#[derive(Default)]\nstruct Mock{Dependency} {\n    results: Arc<Mutex<VecDeque<Result<T, E>>>>,\n}\n\nimpl Mock{Dependency} {\n    fn with_{method}(results: Vec<Result<T, E>>) -> Self { ... }\n    fn for_happy_path() -> Self { ... }\n}\n\n#[async_trait::async_trait]\nimpl Trait for Mock{Dependency} { ... }\n\n// ── §8.1 Contract tests ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n/// AC: {acceptance criteria}\n/// \n/// Detailed explanation of why this test matters.\n#[tokio::test]\nasync fn contract_{scenario_name}() {\n    // Arrange\n    // Act\n    // Assert with detailed messages\n}\n\n// ── §8.2 Integration tests ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n#[tokio::test]\nasync fn integration_{scenario_name}() { ... }\n```\n\n**Module declaration in lib.rs:**\n```rust\n#[cfg(test)]\nmod bridge_mode_acceptance_tests;\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Key Types and Structs Referenced in Contract\n\n**From crates/mcp-runtime/src/contracts.rs:**\n\n```rust\npub struct McpServerRef {\n    pub name: String,\n    pub computer_use_requested: bool,\n    declared_capabilities: BTreeSet<CapabilityLevel>,\n}\n\npub enum CapabilityLevel {\n    Standard,\n    PrivilegedComputerUse,\n}\n\npub trait McpCapabilityPolicy: Send + Sync {\n    fn validate_server_name(&self, name: &str) -> Result<(), McpPolicyError>;\n    fn capability_level(&self, server: &McpServerRef) -> CapabilityLevel;\n}\n\npub trait ComputerUseLifecycle: Send + Sync {\n    async fn before_tool_call(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n    async fn after_turn_cleanup(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n    async fn on_interrupt_cleanup(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n}\n\npub enum McpPolicyError {\n    ReservedServerName,\n    FeatureGateDisabled,\n    PrivilegedCapabilityDenied,\n    TransportError,\n    InvalidToolPayload,\n    CleanupFailed,\n}\n\npub struct DefaultMcpCapabilityPolicy {\n    reserved_server_names: BTreeSet<String>, // Contains \"computer\"\n    allow_privileged_computer_use: bool,\n}\n\npub fn enforce_capability_policy(\n    policy: &dyn McpCapabilityPolicy,\n    server: &McpServerRef,\n    chicago_mcp_feature_gate: bool,\n) -> Result<CapabilityLevel, McpPolicyError>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. Where MCP Code Lives in Codebase\n\n**Crate structure:**\n- `/crates/mcp-runtime/src/` - Core MCP runtime (400 LOC total)\n  - `contracts.rs` - Policy and lifecycle traits (187 LOC with tests)\n  - `client.rs` - JSON-RPC client adapter (140 LOC)\n  - `transport.rs` - Stdio transport implementation (150 LOC)\n  - Tests: Inline with `#[cfg(test)] mod` directives\n\n- `/crates/tools/src/mcp.rs` - MCP tool adapter for discovery and execution\n  - `discover_mcp_tools()` - Launches MCP servers, enforces policy, discovers tools\n  - `McpToolAdapter` - ToolPort implementation for dispatching tool calls\n  - `is_disconnect_error()`, `format_tool_result()` - Helpers\n  - Tests: Inline in same file, 60 LOC\n\n- `/crates/config/src/schema.rs` - Configuration schema\n  - `McpConfig` - Contains `enable_chicago_mcp_feature_gate`, `allow_privileged_computer_use`, servers\n  - `McpServerConfig` - Individual server registration: name, command, args, declared_capabilities, enable_computer_use\n\n- `/crates/application/src/commands/agent_run.rs` - Integration point\n  - `ComputerUseLifecycle` trait (different from mcp-runtime version, wraps it)\n  - Lifecycle hooks called during tool execution loop\n  - Tests: 3 integration tests for lifecycle behavior\n\n- `/crates/bootstrap/tests/spec_governance_gate.rs` - Contract enforcement\n  - Validates required traits exist: `McpCapabilityPolicy`, `ComputerUseLifecycle`\n  - Validates required errors exist: `McpPolicyError`, `McpRuntimeError`\n\n---\n\n### 5. Existing Acceptance Test Suites (US-036, US-037) Patterns\n\n**US-037 Bridge Mode (crates/application/src/bridge_mode_acceptance_tests.rs):**\n- File: 352 LOC\n- Pattern: Full acceptance test suite covering contract + integration tests\n- Structure:\n  1. Mock implementation of external dependency (MockCcrClient)\n  2. Helper functions for test data (sample_create_request, summary_for)\n  3. Helper for short timeout configurations\n  4. Contract tests (§8.1) - 4 tests covering HTTP 409 handling, ID preservation, auth errors\n  5. Integration tests (§8.2) - multi-step lifecycle flows with timing\n- Test doubles: MockCcrClient with VecDeque-based result queueing\n- Assertions: Detailed error messages with context\n\n**Test organization pattern:**\n```\n// ── shared test doubles ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// MockCcrClient, helper builders\n\n// ── §8.1 Contract tests ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// Low-level invariant tests with minimal dependencies\n\n// ── §8.2 Integration tests ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// Multi-step flows exercising real interactions\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. Test Dependencies Available\n\n**From Cargo.toml files:**\n\n**crates/mcp-runtime/Cargo.toml:**\n```toml\n[dependencies]\nasync-trait = { workspace = true }\nthiserror = { workspace = true }\nserde_json = { workspace = true }\ntokio = { workspace = true, features = [\"io-util\", \"process\"] }\n```\n\n**Test utilities commonly available:**\n- `tokio::sync::Mutex` - Async mutex for test state\n- `std::collections::VecDeque` - For queueing mock results\n- `std::sync::Arc` - Sharing mocks across tests\n- `std::sync::atomic::AtomicUsize` - Counting invocations\n- `async_trait::async_trait` - Async trait implementations in tests\n\n**Test macros:**\n- `#[tokio::test]` - Async test runner\n- `#[test]` - Sync test runner\n- `#[cfg(test)]` - Test-only modules\n\n---\n\n### 7. Where US-038 Tests Should Go\n\nBased on the governance rules in `spec_governance_gate.rs`:\n\n```rust\nContractRule {\n    codename: \"CHICAGO_MCP\",\n    doc: \"chicago-mcp-contract.md\",\n    required_traits: &[\"McpCapabilityPolicy\", \"ComputerUseLifecycle\"],\n    required_errors: &[\"McpPolicyError\", \"McpRuntimeError\"],\n    allowed_trait_crates: &[\"crates/mcp-runtime/\"],\n    requires_cli_or_security_matrix: true,\n}\n```\n\n**Recommended test file locations for US-038:**\n1. **Contract tests** → `/crates/mcp-runtime/src/chicago_mcp_acceptance_tests.rs`\n   - Tests for `McpCapabilityPolicy`, `ComputerUseLifecycle`, policy enforcement\n   - Tests for error taxonomy (ReservedServerName, FeatureGateDisabled, etc.)\n   \n2. **Integration tests** → Same file, §8.2 section\n   - MCP server discovery with policy enforcement\n   - Tool execution with lifecycle hooks\n   \n3. **CLI behavior tests** → `/crates/cli/src/cmd/chicago.rs` (or similar)\n   - Error output formatting\n   - Feature gate behavior\n\n4. **Existing unit tests** → Inline in:\n   - `/crates/mcp-runtime/src/contracts.rs` - Already has 3 inline tests\n   - `/crates/tools/src/mcp.rs` - Already has 2 inline tests covering policy\n\n---\n\n### 8. Test Helpers and Utilities Already Available\n\n**Mock pattern from existing tests:**\n- VecDeque-based result queueing for method mocking\n- `#[derive(Default)]` for mock builders\n- Builder methods: `with_create()`, `with_get()`, `for_happy_path()`\n- `#[async_trait]` for implementing async traits in tests\n\n**Mock implementations to follow:**\n```rust\n#[derive(Default)]\nstruct MockPolicy {\n    should_reject: bool,\n}\n\nimpl McpCapabilityPolicy for MockPolicy {\n    fn validate_server_name(&self, name: &str) -> Result<(), McpPolicyError> {\n        if self.should_reject {\n            Err(McpPolicyError::ReservedServerName)\n        } else {\n            Ok(())\n        }\n    }\n    \n    fn capability_level(&self, server: &McpServerRef) -> CapabilityLevel {\n        CapabilityLevel::Standard\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Lifecycle testing pattern from agent_run.rs tests:**\n```rust\n#[derive(Default)]\nstruct MockLifecycle {\n    before_calls: AtomicUsize,\n    cleanup_calls: AtomicUsize,\n    interrupt_cleanup_calls: AtomicUsize,\n    fail_cleanup: bool,\n}\n\n#[async_trait]\nimpl ComputerUseLifecycle for MockLifecycle { ... }\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Files Reference\n\n| File Path | Purpose | LOC |\n|-----------|---------|-----|\n| `/docs/chicago-mcp-contract.md` | Contract specification | 93 |\n| `/crates/mcp-runtime/src/contracts.rs` | Core traits + error types | 187 |\n| `/crates/mcp-runtime/src/client_tests.rs` | Transport integration tests | 100 |\n| `/crates/tools/src/mcp.rs` | Tool discovery + policy enforcement | 225 |\n| `/crates/config/src/schema.rs` | MCP configuration schema | ~50 relevant |\n| `/crates/application/src/commands/agent_run.rs` | Lifecycle integration | 630+ with tests |\n| `/crates/application/src/bridge_mode_acceptance_tests.rs` | Test pattern reference | 352 |\n| `/crates/bootstrap/tests/spec_governance_gate.rs` | Contract governance | 200+ |\n\n---\n\nThis comprehensive overview provides everything needed to write acceptance tests for US-038 that align with exis