{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QUT18kR5653SqWEppfrRWZ","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# CHICAGO_MCP Contract Spec (Rust)\n2\t\n3\t## 1. Objective\n4\t\n5\tDefine Rust contracts for computer-use MCP while isolating high-privilege behavior from generic MCP runtime.\n6\t\n7\t## 2. Evidence from Current Code\n8\t\n9\t1. `entrypoints/cli.tsx:86` `--computer-use-mcp` fast path.\n10\t2. `services/mcp/client.ts:241` lazy wrapper under `feature('CHICAGO_MCP')`.\n11\t3. `services/mcp/config.ts:641` reserved-name policy when CHICAGO_MCP enabled.\n12\t4. `services/mcp/config.ts:1512` built-in default disabled behavior.\n13\t5. `query.ts:1033` turn-end cleanup on interrupt path.\n14\t6. `query.ts:1489` cleanup on normal path.\n15\t7. `utils/computerUse/wrapper.tsx` wrapper-level gate and call override semantics.\n16\t8. `utils/computerUse/cleanup.ts` cleanup contract.\n17\t\n18\t## 3. Rust Boundary Mapping\n19\t\n20\t1. `crates/api-types`: MCP tool request/response and capability metadata.\n21\t2. `crates/mcp-runtime`: protocol transport and server lifecycle.\n22\t3. `crates/tool-runtime`: tool registration/dispatch pipeline.\n23\t4. `crates/platform`: native lock/host adapter/process boundaries.\n24\t5. `crates/config`: gate keys, reserved-name policy flags.\n25\t\n26\t## 4. Core Contracts (Rust Sketch)\n27\t\n28\t```rust\n29\t#[derive(Debug, Clone)]\n30\tpub struct McpServerRef { pub name: String }\n31\t\n32\t#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]\n33\tpub enum CapabilityLevel { Standard, PrivilegedComputerUse }\n34\t\n35\t#[async_trait::async_trait]\n36\tpub trait McpCapabilityPolicy {\n37\t    fn validate_server_name(&self, name: &str) -> Result<(), McpPolicyError>;\n38\t    fn capability_level(&self, server: &McpServerRef) -> CapabilityLevel;\n39\t}\n40\t\n41\t#[async_trait::async_trait]\n42\tpub trait ComputerUseLifecycle {\n43\t    async fn before_tool_call(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n44\t    async fn after_turn_cleanup(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n45\t    async fn on_interrupt_cleanup(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n46\t}\n47\t```\n48\t\n49\t## 5. Error Taxonomy\n50\t\n51\t1. `ReservedServerName`\n52\t2. `FeatureGateDisabled`\n53\t3. `PrivilegedCapabilityDenied`\n54\t4. `TransportError`\n55\t5. `InvalidToolPayload`\n56\t6. `CleanupFailed` (non-fatal in interrupt path)\n57\t\n58\t## 6. Policy Rules\n59\t\n60\t1. Reserved names are hard-rejected before persistence.\n61\t2. Privileged computer-use adapter requires gate + policy pass.\n62\t3. Cleanup must run in both normal and interrupt paths.\n63\t4. Cleanup failures are observable but do not crash the main turn path.\n64\t\n65\t## 7. Constants Classification\n66\t\n67\t1. `api-types`: MCP event labels and capability enums.\n68\t2. `config`: `CHICAGO_MCP` related gate keys and defaults.\n69\t3. `core-domain`: privileged transition invariants.\n70\t4. `mcp-runtime`/`platform`: wrapper and adapter internals.\n71\t5. `ui-tui`: display messages only.\n72\t\n73\t## 8. Acceptance Matrix\n74\t\n75\t### Contract tests\n76\t\n77\t1. Reserved names rejected with `ReservedServerName`.\n78\t2. Privileged capability denied without gate/policy.\n79\t3. Cleanup API is called for both normal and interrupt exits.\n80\t\n81\t### Integration tests\n82\t\n83\t1. MCP server registration + tool dispatch happy path.\n84\t2. Interrupt during tool call triggers cleanup once.\n85\t3. Cleanup exception does not poison subsequent turns.\n86\t\n87\t### CLI behavior tests\n88\t\n89\t1. `--computer-use-mcp` routes to privileged adapter path.\n90\t2. Error output exposes class, not sensitive native details.\n91\t3. Disabled gate path gives deterministic reason.\n92\t\n93\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"523981ce-25d5-4aed-a492-78dcbb263a10","uuid":"743685a4-327c-4d7d-8ccf-e675092b22cc","timestamp":"2026-04-02T14:22:56.004Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/yaxin/Projects/rust_projects/ccode/docs/chicago-mcp-contract.md","content":"# CHICAGO_MCP Contract Spec (Rust)\n\n## 1. Objective\n\nDefine Rust contracts for computer-use MCP while isolating high-privilege behavior from generic MCP runtime.\n\n## 2. Evidence from Current Code\n\n1. `entrypoints/cli.tsx:86` `--computer-use-mcp` fast path.\n2. `services/mcp/client.ts:241` lazy wrapper under `feature('CHICAGO_MCP')`.\n3. `services/mcp/config.ts:641` reserved-name policy when CHICAGO_MCP enabled.\n4. `services/mcp/config.ts:1512` built-in default disabled behavior.\n5. `query.ts:1033` turn-end cleanup on interrupt path.\n6. `query.ts:1489` cleanup on normal path.\n7. `utils/computerUse/wrapper.tsx` wrapper-level gate and call override semantics.\n8. `utils/computerUse/cleanup.ts` cleanup contract.\n\n## 3. Rust Boundary Mapping\n\n1. `crates/api-types`: MCP tool request/response and capability metadata.\n2. `crates/mcp-runtime`: protocol transport and server lifecycle.\n3. `crates/tool-runtime`: tool registration/dispatch pipeline.\n4. `crates/platform`: native lock/host adapter/process boundaries.\n5. `crates/config`: gate keys, reserved-name policy flags.\n\n## 4. Core Contracts (Rust Sketch)\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Clone)]\npub struct McpServerRef { pub name: String }\n\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq)]\npub enum CapabilityLevel { Standard, PrivilegedComputerUse }\n\n#[async_trait::async_trait]\npub trait McpCapabilityPolicy {\n    fn validate_server_name(&self, name: &str) -> Result<(), McpPolicyError>;\n    fn capability_level(&self, server: &McpServerRef) -> CapabilityLevel;\n}\n\n#[async_trait::async_trait]\npub trait ComputerUseLifecycle {\n    async fn before_tool_call(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n    async fn after_turn_cleanup(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n    async fn on_interrupt_cleanup(&self) -> Result<(), McpRuntimeError>;\n}\n```\n\n## 5. Error Taxonomy\n\n1. `ReservedServerName`\n2. `FeatureGateDisabled`\n3. `PrivilegedCapabilityDenied`\n4. `TransportError`\n5. `InvalidToolPayload`\n6. `CleanupFailed` (non-fatal in interrupt path)\n\n## 6. Policy Rules\n\n1. Reserved names are hard-rejected before persistence.\n2. Privileged computer-use adapter requires gate + policy pass.\n3. Cleanup must run in both normal and interrupt paths.\n4. Cleanup failures are observable but do not crash the main turn path.\n\n## 7. Constants Classification\n\n1. `api-types`: MCP event labels and capability enums.\n2. `config`: `CHICAGO_MCP` related gate keys and defaults.\n3. `core-domain`: privileged transition invariants.\n4. `mcp-runtime`/`platform`: wrapper and adapter internals.\n5. `ui-tui`: display messages only.\n\n## 8. Acceptance Matrix\n\n### Contract tests\n\n1. Reserved names rejected with `ReservedServerName`.\n2. Privileged capability denied without gate/policy.\n3. Cleanup API is called for both normal and interrupt exits.\n\n### Integration tests\n\n1. MCP server registration + tool dispatch happy path.\n2. Interrupt during tool call triggers cleanup once.\n3. Cleanup exception does not poison subsequent turns.\n\n### CLI behavior tests\n\n1. `--computer-use-mcp` routes to privileged adapter path.\n2. Error output exposes class, not sensitive native details.\n3. Disabled gate path gives deterministic reason.\n\n","numLines":93,"startLine":1,"totalLines":93}}}
